      "slideId": 1,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Introduction to Archiving & Compression"
        },
        {
          "type": "definition",
          "value": "Archiving and compression allow us to combine multiple files or folders and reduce their size so they are easier to store, transfer, or back up."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Linux uses tools like tar, zip, and gzip to create compressed archives. These help save disk space, package project files, and share data efficiently."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Tool", "Purpose"],
            ["tar", "Archive multiple files together (can compress too)"],
            ["zip", "Create compressed .zip files (cross-platform friendly)"],
            ["unzip", "Extract .zip files"],
            ["gzip", "Compress a single file (.gz format)"],
            ["gunzip", "Extract .gz compressed files"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "tar is most common in Linux; zip is best for sharing with Windows users."
        }
      ],
      "video": {
        "platform": "youtube",
        "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KucqplDh7LI"
      }
    },



    {
      "slideId": 2,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Working With tar Archives (.tar, .tar.gz)"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "tar is the standard Linux tool for archiving folders and optionally compressing them using gzip."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "tar -cf archive.tar foldername/",
          "description": "Create an archive (no compression)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "tar -czf archive.tar.gz foldername/",
          "description": "Create a compressed archive (.tar.gz)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "tar -xzf archive.tar.gz",
          "description": "Extract a compressed archive."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Flag", "Meaning"],
            ["-c", "Create archive"],
            ["-x", "Extract archive"],
            ["-z", "Compress using gzip"],
            ["-f", "File name will follow"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Remember: c = create, x = extract, z = zip compression, f = file"
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },



    {
      "slideId": 3,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Working With zip & gzip Compression"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "zip is easier for sharing with Windows users, while gzip is commonly used for single files in Linux."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "zip myfiles.zip file1 file2 file3",
          "description": "Create a zip archive."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "unzip myfiles.zip",
          "description": "Extract a .zip archive."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "gzip file.txt",
          "description": "Compress a single file into file.txt.gz"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "gunzip file.txt.gz",
          "description": "Decompress a .gz file"
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Use zip for folders, gzip for large single files."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },



    {
